The data obtained from potentiodynamic polarization tests conducted on Paint 1 through Paint 4 were meticulously analyzed (refer to Table 3
                           ). In Fig. 7
                           , the cathodic and anodic Tafel slopes are presented, offering valuable insights into the corrosion kinetics. The data values presented in Table 3 offer detailed insights into the corrosion behavior and corrosion protection efficiency of the paint formulations containing varying concentrations of BC-CNDs. Starting with Paint 1, the highest corrosion current density (0.065 μA/cm2) suggests a comparatively higher corrosion rate (El Hajjaji et al., 2018; Karakosta et al., 2021). However, as the concentration of BC-CNDs increases in Paints 2, 3, and 4, there is a consistent decrease in corrosion current densities, indicating improved corrosion resistance with higher BC-CND concentrations. Concurrently, the corrosion potentials (Ecorr) become more negative with increasing BC-CND concentrations, implying a greater tendency for mild steel corrosion at higher BC-CND concentrations. Notably, Paint 4 demonstrates the most negative corrosion potential (287.12 μA/cm2), suggesting enhanced corrosion protection compared to other formulations. Furthermore, both the anodic (βa) and cathodic (βc) Tafel slopes tend to decrease as BC-CND concentrations increase. Lower Tafel slopes indicate faster reaction rates, signifying that the addition of BC-CNDs suppresses both anodic and cathodic corrosion reactions. Additionally, the corrosion protection efficiency, expressed as a percentage, notably increases with higher concentrations of BC-CNDs. Paint 4 exhibits the highest corrosion protection efficiency (89.36%), indicating superior corrosion protection compared to other formulations (Kamaruzzaman et al., 2022; Dastpak et al., 2018). This observation further bolsters the notion that BC-CNDs play a crucial role in mitigating the corrosion process. Moreover, by forming a protective barrier between the solution and the exterior surface of mild steel, BC-CNDs effectively prevented chloride ion assault, thereby enhancing the overall corrosion resistance of the coated specimens. This multifaceted analysis underscores the significant contribution of BC-CNDs in inhibiting corrosion and highlights their potential as effective corrosion inhibitors in practical applications.

Electrochemical Impedance Spectroscopy was used to examine the corrosion behaviors of specimens immersed in acid with four different percentages of CNDs. The gathered data were displayed in Nyquist plots (Fig. 8
                           ). It is noteworthy that all impedance spectra exhibited a similar characteristic form, characterized by a single capacitive semi-circle. This characteristic suggests that the corrosion process was primarily controlled by charge transfer mechanisms (Farhadian et al., 2021). The results of our study (Table 4
                           ) revealed that the presence of BC-CNDs in the paint, particularly in the case of matrix paint 4, led to a significant increase in the polarization resistance (Rp) value. Specifically, Rp increased from 1782.2 Ω cm2 to 4778.3 Ω cm2 when BC-CNDs were incorporated. It is important to note that an increase in Rp indicates improved inhibitory effectiveness. This enhancement can be attributed to the formation of passive films on the surface of the specimens, which act as a protective barrier against corrosion. Furthermore, the capacitance of the double layer (Cdl) exhibited a noteworthy change, decreasing from 0.003791 F to 0.000285 F. This reduction in Cdl suggests that the presence of BC-CNDs had a significant impact on the electrical double layer at the metal-electrolyte interface. Such changes in Cdl are indicative of alterations in the electrochemical behavior associated with the corrosion process.
